data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, **new built-in span conversions** cause `array.Contains(value)` on `int[]` to resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

Expression trees **cannot represent** `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` method calls, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the call to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option A: Cast in the expression
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option B: Use AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option C: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler to pick the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which expression trees support. This also applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — same fix pattern.
